Perspectives for Sino-American Relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations had unsettled wide parts of Asia.
One year ago, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly flamboyant "State Visit Plus" in Beijing, where China hoped that Trump's anti-Chinese election rhetoric would finally be a thing of the past.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are embroiled in a trade war, and the US approach to China has been replaced by "strategic competition" from the Trump administration.
In addition, the US, European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming one year ago.
Today there is great uncertainty in financial markets, growth is slowing in China and Europe, and higher interest rates in America are beginning to take effect.
The uncertainty about the future development of nuclear talks with North Korea also clouds the picture.
So what are the prospects for Sino-American relations in 2019?
It is likely that an agreement on reducing the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions that China will make regarding this will be reached by March.
An agreement on tariff reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could prolong the envisaged timeframe.
If each tariff is negotiated one by one, it could take a whole year.
However, if Chinese economic reformers opt for a more radical approach by gradually eliminating all tariffs and urging Americans to do the same, faster results might be achieved.
This, however, would go against Chinese customs officials who have been trained for decades to be reluctant, let alone generous with everything at once.
The reform of so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively uncomplicated.
Nevertheless, a reform is something different from how contractual agreements might be interpreted in practice, even if there should not be any specific provisions on technology transfer.
The protection of intellectual property is however extremely problematic.
Prior agreements made under President Barack Obama's administration could potentially be reaffirmed.
Enforcing these or pursuing legal action for infringement of intellectual property rights remains a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism would be to subject relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international arbitration bodies based in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically tasked with enforcing intellectual property protection.
If China objects, it could develop its own international arbitration institution based in China.
For this, it would have to convene qualified foreigners in its arbitration body to strengthen its international credibility.
Noone has confidence in Chinese trade courts.
To meet its own domestic reform needs, China must move towards completely independent trade and civil chambers within its judicial system, even though the criminal chamber remains subject to political control.
The concerns of the United States regarding state subsidies as part of the country's "Made in China 2025" strategy will hardly be resolved.
The fact is that all countries provide some degree of state support to their domestic technology sectors, although this is highest in China.
Even if we were to prescribe a maximum level of state support for a specific company, adherence would be hard to verify.
I am not optimistic that a negotiation outcome will be reached in this area.
Maybe America simply has to knock China out of the race by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China offers customs reforms to the rest of the international community.
Over time, China might decide to take such a drastic step as to agree to free trade not only with the USA but with all members of the World Trade Organization.
Auf diese Weise böte sich China eine nahezu unwiderstehliche Gelegenheit, sich als Verfechter des globalen Freihandels zu positionieren und dem Trend zum Protektionismus Einhalt zu gebieten.
Im Zuge einer solchen Wende könnte China die Mitgliedstaaten des transpazifischen Freihandelsabkommens TPP um einen Beitritt ersuchen, um die USA (die als eine der ersten Amtshandlungen Trumps aus dem Freihandelsabkommen ausgestiegen sind) in der Region Asien-Pazifik zu überflügeln.
China kann bemerkenswert leichtfüßig sein, wenn es eine politische Bresche und Marktöffnung entdeckt.
Die Verhandlungen wären schwierig, aber die Vorbehalte Japans gegenüber dem Beitritt Chinas zum TPP haben sich seit dem jüngsten Besuch von Ministerpräsident Shinzo Abe in Peking verringert.
Angesichts der zentralen strategischen Herausforderungen im Verhältnis zu den USA, dürfte China 2019 in der allgemeinen Außen- und Sicherheitspolitik bestrebt sein, Konflikte in seinen Beziehungen zu anderen Ländern abzubauen.
In the relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from the Japanese Coast Guard indicate a significant reduction in Chinese incursions into the East China Sea around the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands.
China wants to ease tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations regarding the South China Sea through accelerated negotiations of a "Code of Conduct".
Furthermore, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India after the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could begin to moderate its stance toward Taiwan, given the electoral setback suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party of Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen, which supports independence, in local and regional elections last month.
This would naturally change dramatically if the US continues with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
There continue to be incidents at sea with the US in the South China Sea, and the conflict could intensify if the US makes its stance on "freedom of navigation" more assertive next year.
Across Eurasia, China will continue to implement its grand project, the Belt and Road Initiative.
However, in recent months, the initiative in China has caused less political stir.
Among Chinese officials, there are already discussions about revising certain modalities, following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns about the long-term financing of the Belt and Road Initiative.
2019 could therefore see fewer triumphant reports on the New Silk Road.
Moreover, China is likely to strengthen and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions rather than highlight new institutions of international political conduct.
It will probably continue to present itself as a new champion of the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More sober-minded representatives of China's foreign-policy establishment believe it is better to focus on the existing mechanisms of the global rules-based system, especially if the United States consistently shows contempt for it.
While China tries to stabilize its relations with the United States and reduce tensions in its relationships with other countries, its leadership will likely use 2019 to form a solid judgment on the future of US policy: the consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his government, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would alter the new US strategy in any way.
Although they have concluded that the US attitude towards China has fundamentally changed, they are uncertain about the exact form this change takes and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is appropriate.
